   <li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="li-comment-45436">
      <div class="comment_author">
         <img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/50f6c108ddbaaafe84316c115e1e2783?s=80&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D80&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' />
         <p><cite><a href='http://brighteyesnews.wordpress.com/category/vision-therapy/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Nathan Bonilla-Warford, OD</a></cite></p>
      </div>
      <img src="http://ririanproject.com/wp-content/themes/evolutionary/images/misc/comment.png" alt="" class="commentimg" />
      <div class="comment_text_container">
      	<div class="comment_text">
	  	      		<p>#3 &#8220;“Some eye exercises can improve your vision” is totally false. If you are going to make statements of a medical nature, it is inappropriate to fail to include citations. There are activities that can improve visual skill for any person. Go to <a href="http://www.covd.org/" rel="nofollow">http://www.covd.org/</a> to learn more.</p>
<p>Even if you are solely referring to visual acuity, the statement is still false. A small group of people can improve their vision, if they have &#8220;pseudo-myopia&#8221; or temporary myopia that is caused by near vision strain. This can be improved with glasses, but can only be truly resolved with vision therapy.</p>
<p>In the future, please check your facts before you perpetuate more myths. Either than or stick to something that you are knowledgeable about.</p>
    	  </div>
